or cura were secured against loss from the dishonesty or negligence oi their tutors or curators. They were also protected (1) by the possibility oi remotio, Tit 26 ini. These were the affirmatores, who had at the inquisitio borne witness to the character ol the person appointed, and the nominatores, persons who proposed or suggested a tutor or curator in any particular case; this might happen (a) at the petitio tutoris. lfa pupil had no tutor, anyone could apply soror suggest one, and some persons were bound to do this: eg. the mother (Blc iii. 3. 6 ini), and other heirs presumptive ab intestato, under penalty, in deiault, ol forfeiting their rights of succession ii the pupil died impubes, Dig. 26. 6. 2. 2: also the libertus, under a pecuniary penalty, Dig. 16. 2. r. (b) ln cases where a man was appointed tutor or curator by a magistrate, he could usually procure exemption by suggesting some one better qualified (potioris nominatio) by reason of relationship.
